[2] Nigeria
Date: 14 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: All Africa 12 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200410120557.html>

Polio: Nigeria, 22 Others Immunize 80m
Dec 2005 now target for eradication
------------------------
As the 4th round of National Immunization Days (NIDs) ends today
across the country, over 80 million children in 22 other countries of
sub-Saharan Africa including west and central Africa, would have been
immunized by an estimated one million vaccinators.
The synchronized immunization campaign, reputed to be the
largest-ever bid to beat polio, local and international health
workers in collaboration with traditional and religious leaders,
school teachers, parents, Rotary Club, and Red Cross members and
other volunteers, joined nurses and a vast array of other health
workers going house-to-house and village-to-village to ensure the
vaccine got to every child under the age of 5 years.
The campaign comes one month after an emergency meeting in Geneva
where health ministers of the 6 remaining polio-endemic countries --
Afghanistan, Egypt, India, Niger, Nigeria and Pakistan -- committed
themselves to end polio transmission in 2004 with a bold new plan for
the mass immunisation of a total of 250 million children.
Previously, before the campaign kicked of Friday last week, a total
of 786 polio cases had been reported globally in 2004 down from over
125 reported cases when the Global Polio Eradication Initiative (PEI)
was launched in 1988 by WHO, Rotary International, the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, and UNICEF. So far about US $3
billion has been expended on the initiative.
To date Nigeria tops the list with 597 cases compared with 178 cases
at about the same time in 2003. It is followed by India (62),
Pakistan (31), Niger (20), Afghanistan (3) and Egypt (1). Countries
with imported cases included Benin Republic (6 cases), Botswana (1),
Burkina Faso (6), Cameroon (2), the Central African Republic (12),
Chad (16), Cote d'Ivoire (15), Guinea (1), Mali (2) and the Sudan
(11).
Currently, the country accounts for about 77 per cent of the global
wild polio virus cases-count and 88 per cent of the cases in Africa
since January 2004. It is expected that with the latest NIDs,
transmission of the polio virus could stop completely by early 2005.
It is further believed that if the campaigns reach enough children in
the region's hotspots, polio transmission could be expected to slow
significantly.
The latest anti-polio drive is spearheaded by th World Health
organization and other partners in the Global Initiative -- Rotary
International, the United States Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDC) and UNICEF.
In Lagos State, one of the 4 where the wild polio virus is confirmed
to still be circulating, an estimated 3 million children were
immunized. Speaking to Good Health Weekly shortly after the event
commenced, the state's Commissioner for Health, Dr. Leke Pitan said
about 120 000 personnel were mobilized for the activity. Armed with
500 000 doses of the OPV, the men and women who made up the 479 sweep
teams combed 400 000 homes to ensure that every child within the
target age was reached with the life-saving oral drops.
[Announcing the] recommendations of the Expert Review Committee on
polio Eradication, Pitan stressed that the new target date to
interrupt transmission of the polio virus had been extended till the
end of 2005 from the former December 2004 target date.
On attaining this objective, Pitan stressed, there would be intensive
activities for the next 12 months after the last detected wild polio
virus, and this is expected to go on right through 2006. A mop-up
exercise will follow in the first half of 2006, after which
certification processes will take off in 2007.
Nigeria's suspension of immunisation campaigns in key northern
states, particularly Kano, remains the greatest challenge for a quick
end to polio in Africa. Until mid-2003, Nigeria was part of Africa's
polio success story, with only a few northern states still endemic
with the virus and Lagos polio-free for over 2 years. The suspension
of immunisation campaigns in Kano and the subsequent outbreak of
polio in that area were fueled by unfounded rumours about the safety
of polio vaccine.
In recent months, polio has again spread across West and Central
Africa from Nigeria, paralysing children in 7 previously polio-free
countries -- most recently in the Central African Republic -- and
putting millions more at risk [see Polio Eradication report below
[5], the number of countries reinfected as a result of the ongoing
transmission in Nigeria is 10 - Mod.MPP]. But partners in the Global
Polio Eradication Initiative say that if upcoming campaigns over the
next several months reach every child, polio in Africa could be
stopped in its tracks already this year.
[Byline: Sola Ogundipe]
