[3] Nigeria
Date: 14 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: All Africa 11 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200410110026.html>

UNICEF Confirms Re-Emergence of Polio Virus
-------------------
UNICEF has confirmed the re-emergence [, as evidenced by] about 210
cases, of wild polio virus in some states under the zone D office of
the world body.
The communication officer of the Bauchi Zonal Office of UNICEF,
Alhaji Mohammed Anka announced this figure in Bauchi recently at a
forum of Directors of the National Orientation Agency (NOA) from 10
States within the zone.
The forum, at the instance of the Bauchi State office of the NOA with
support from UNICEF, discussed effective strategies for the
implementation of a new action plan for the eradication of wild
poliovirus in the most endemic states of the zone.
According to the UNICEF Spokesman, "Kano State has the highest rate
of wild polio virus with 127 assorted cases followed by Jigawa with
37; Bauchi 18; Borno 12 and Yobe 9", adding that Taraba, Plateau and
Nasarawa States have 2 cases each".
Anka warned politicians and religious leaders against toying with the
lives of innocent children through their unwarranted utterances that
lacked scientific proof, allegations difficult to substantiate.
[Byline: Segun Awofadeji]
