[4] Sudan
Date: 14 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters 13 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/9bc3e5670714811a0c5c270039f0b8db.htm>

New polio cases prompt enhanced immunisation campaign
-----------------------
11 confirmed cases of polio were reported in Sudan this year,
prompting 2 United Nations agencies and an international
non-governmental organisation to step up efforts to stem the spread
of the crippling and sometimes fatal disease, the UN Children's Fund
(UNICEF) said on Wednesday.
Most of the [viruses detected in samples taken from] cases were
genetically linked to the polio virus endemic in northern Nigeria,
UNICEF said in a statement. UNICEF was working with with the UN World
Health Organization (WHO) and Rotary International in the fight
against the spread of polio, it added.
Sudan had been polio-free since April 2001, but cross-border movement
between Chad and Sudan is believed to have re-introduced the virus.
The conflict in the western region of Darfur, where the 1st of the 11
cases was noticed, prevented the immunisation of all children under
the age of 5 years.
"Armed conflict has contributed to the re-infection by the wild polio
virus in Darfur that has now spread to the capital city, Khartoum,"
the WHO representative in Sudan, Guido Sabatinelli, said in the
statement.
The 1st of 2 rounds of national immunisation days was concluded on 12
Oct 2004. The 2nd round is scheduled for 21-23 Nov 2004, targeting 6
million children.
The campaigns are part of a larger, regional immunisation effort in
23 countries across west and central Africa that aims to immunize
more than 80 million children in a bid to urgently stop the spread of
the polio virus that originated in northern Nigeria.
